  "prompt": "Is an MBA (core) different from a normal MBA?",
  "response": "An MBA (Core) and a standard MBA can have some differences:\n\nMBA (Core):\n1. More focused on fundamental business principles\n2. Typically covers standard business management topics\n3. Generally follows a more traditional curriculum\n4. Less specialized or customized\n5. Provides broad-based business knowledge\n6. Often has a more structured learning approach\n\nStandard MBA:\n1. Can have various specializations (e.g., Finance, Marketing, Technology)\n2. May offer more flexible course selections\n3. Often includes elective courses\n4. Can be more tailored to specific industry or career goals\n5. Sometimes includes more practical, industry-specific content\n6. May have different learning formats (online, part-time, executive)\n\nWhile both provide business management education, the core MBA tends to be more generalized, while a standard MBA can be more customizable. The exact differences can vary between institutions.\n\nTo get precise details, it's best to check specific program descriptions from individual universities or business schools.",
